RBC and plasma recovery

I have calculated the plasma recovery and red cell recovery using the following steps. I need to calculate the volume of the flowdown. If I chose not to dilute my blood with PBS, I would have a binary mixture of plasma and RBCs. Since Im adding PBS though, I have a ternary mixture and cannot use the reference plasma density of 1024 \(kg/m^3\). Because I can only obtain the volume fraction of red blood cells in the flowdown, I have an extra degree of freedom. To remove this, I will simplify this system back to binary by making a composite (i.e.solution) density between PBS and plasma as a function of their volumes. \[ m_{solution} = \rho_{PBS}V_{PBS} + \rho_{plasma}(1-HCT_{whole\;blood})V_{whole\;blood}\] \[ \rho_{solution} = \frac{m_{solution}}{V_{whole\;blood}(1-HCT_{whole\;blood})+V_{PBS}} \] The volume fraction of plasma in solution is \[\nu_{plasma} = \frac{V_{whole\;blood}(1-HCT_{whole\;blood})}{V_{whole\;blood}(1-HCT_{whole\;blood})+V_{PBS}}\] The mass of the flowdown is measured directly. It can be represented as a ternary mixture \(\sum{\rho_{i}V_{i}}, \;\;i=WB, plasma, PBS\) or as a binary mixture using the \(\rho_{solution}\) just calculated. This latter approach will be used for the remainder of the derivation. \[ m_{flowdown} = \rho_{solution}V_{solution}+\rho_{RBC}V_{RBC} \] Moving to the next step require the intermediate values: \(V_{solution} = V_{flowdown}(1-HCT_{flowdown})\) and \(V_{RBC} = V_{flowdown}HCT_{flowdown}\). Substituting these values into the equation above yields:

\[ m_{flowdown} = V_{flowdown}[\rho_{solution}(1-HCT_{flowdown})+\rho_{RBC}HCT_{whole\;blood}] \]

A simple rearrangement gives \(V_{flowdown}\) in the following expression:

\[ V_{flowdown} = \frac{m_{flowdown}}{\rho_{solution}(1-HCT_{plasma})+\rho_{RBC}HCT_{whole\;blood}} \] Now the Plasma and RBC recoveries can be calculated \[Plasma \; Recovery \;(\%) = \frac{\nu_{plasma}V_{flowdown}(1-HCT_{flowdown})}{V_{PBS} + V_{whole\;blood}(1-HCT_{whole \;blood})}*100\]

\[ RBC \; Recovery \;(\%) = \frac{V_{flowdown}HCT_{flowdown}}{V_{whole\;blood}HCT_{whole\;blood}}*100\]

Temp = 23 #C
rho_PBS <- -5.2037e-6*Temp^2 - 8.1463e-6*Temp + 1.0097 
# I got this correlation from
# (http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S003991400400373X)

spins$VolFracPlasma  <- with(spins,{VolWB*(1-HCT)/(VolWB*(1-HCT) + VolPBS)})
spins$RhoSolution    <- with(spins,{(rho_PBS*VolPBS + 1.024*(1-HCT)*VolWB)/(VolPBS + (1-HCT)*VolWB)})
spins$VFlowdown      <- with(spins,{gplas_tot/(RhoSolution*(1-HCT_plas)+1.093*HCT_plas)})
spins[is.na(spins$HCT_plas),]$VFlowdown <- spins[is.na(spins$HCT_plas),]$gplas_tot/1.024
# Some disks have missing HCT_plasma values. For these disks, I approximate the density of the
# flowdown as that of pure plasma. This lets me keep these data with little introduced error.

spins$RBCRecovery    <- with(spins,{VFlowdown*VolFracPlasma*HCT_plas/(VolWB*HCT)*100})
spins$PlasmaRecovery <- with(spins,{VFlowdown*(1-HCT_plas)/(VolPBS+VolWB*(1-HCT))*100})

The reason most of the glossy disks have higher plasma recovery is because the flowdown is more predictable. With the matte ones, the same maximum flowdown is possible, but the rough surface presents an energy barrier, so a column of liquid with a given force has a lower chance of beating the threshold.

RealVol <- function(x){
       if (x==3){return(x*0.8)}
  else if (x==4){return(x*0.9)}
  else if (x==5){return(x*0.8)}
  else {print('failed')}}

spins$Trough.Volume.real <- RealVol(spins$Trough.Volume)
## Warning in if (x == 3) {: the condition has length > 1 and only the first
## element will be used

The threshold ratio of Red cells to trough volume is not constant for the different trough volumes. I think that the 5mL tubes maybe relax more as the cells descend.

No correlation between trough volume and plasma recovery. Adding the volume of stuck flowdown doesnt change the disk hematocrit hardly at all.

Comparison of Trough hematocrit calculation to experimental

The calcuated Trough hematocrits for 2 experiments on 20.05_16x3_glossy_5mL was 78.4376016, 83.7315333, and the measured values were 83 and 87. The calculated values are lower probably because it considers the whole disk as the trough; in reality, the red cells are more concentrated in the trough than in the flowdown region.

Even though all the disks spill over near the same hematocrit, the hematocrit of what is left in the disk is higher. (I need to check the assumptions of these calculations. and maybe try to factor in the uncollected flowdown.) The plasma-RBC interface may be cleaner because the red cell pack doesnt have as far to move and thus cannot mix..

I may want to do a few experiments with low low HCT for 3mL trough to see where the fluid comes down.

Hypothesis testing

I want to know if the ratio between the volume of red cells and the volume of the trough is constant for every disk. I need to do an analysis of covariance. That ratio will be my intercept if I plot \(Ratio\) vs \(RBC_{recovery}\). Before I look at my intercepts, however, I have to see if the slopes are the same for each disk. Ill hope not.

The Plasma recovery and flowdown volumes seem to decrease with WB hematocrit. Thats a bit weird because I correct for HCT in the recovery calculations.

The total volume recovered decreases with rising hematocrit. The RBC pack should be thicker, so there may be less flowdown because the red cells adhere to each other better than the plasma does Something is keeping fluid from descending when the hematocrit rises. though, I may need more points before I can really conclude that. Ill want to do it with a broader range of donors.

In terms of plasma recovery, its best to do it immediately, or else late. 30s is not a good time. If you do it early, you prevent the plasma from wetting the whole collection area. If you collect late, more plasma has flowed down. If done early, the plasma has more time to come down while youre pipetting.

RBC recovery vs time is difficult to see with really bloody disks. Less bloody disks, however, increase RBC recovery with time. I want to find the threshold hematocrit where RBCs flow down
